        <Rewritten Code>:
        ### cell 25 ###

# 1) Filter for USA and India using GPU-backed isin
us_ind = df[df['first_country'].isin(['USA', 'India'])]

# 2) Compute per-year, per-country counts entirely on the GPU
#    groupby.size() is GPU‐accelerated in cuDF
counts_df = (
    us_ind
    .groupby(['year_added', 'first_country'])
    .size()
    .to_frame('count')
    .reset_index()
)

# 3) Pivot on the GPU (cuDF supports DataFrame.pivot) and fill missing with zeros
counts = (
    counts_df
    .pivot(index='year_added', columns='first_country', values='count')
    .fillna(0)
    .sort_index()
)

# 4) Restrict to ['USA', 'India'] and compute a stacked cumulative sum
#    across the country axis (axis=1) so that:
#      data_sub['USA']  = USA count per year
#      data_sub['India'] = USA + India per year
counts = counts[['USA', 'India']]
data_sub = counts.cumsum(axis=1)

# 5) Insert a zero "base" column for stacked positioning
#    cuDF DataFrame.insert will broadcast the scalar to all rows
data_sub.insert(0, 'base', 0)

# 6) Compute half of the total USA+India counts per year on the GPU
half_counts = us_ind.groupby('year_added').size().div(2)

# 7) Center the stacked areas by subtracting the half-counts
#    Broadcasting subtraction against the index is GPU‐accelerated
data_sub = data_sub - half_counts

# `data_sub` is now semantically identical to the original result but uses only GPU operations
